CHAPTER XVII

CHRISTIAN ENTERPRISE

THE author of the Fourth Gospel, with his deeply spiritual insight‚ sums up the principle of Chris- tianity by representing our Lord as saying, “ I am come that ye might have life, and that ye might have it more abundantly.’'

It is interesting to try to imagine what would have been the result if the Christian Church had from the first laid upon positive commandments the emphasis that it has laid upon the mere nega— tions which embody more primitive morality. A place in Church ritual was needed for the historic repetition of these3 but if in constant repetition at her most sacred service, and in the catechism of the young, the Church had impressed upon the imaginations of her members good things lively and affectionate to be done, instead of bad things not to be done, we cannot doubt that the moral standards of to-day would be different. Would they be worse?
